Blue chip advertisers that long shunned Fox News (or at least its more
crackpot-friendly time slots) are quietly coming back, leading the network =
to record-setting revenue. Is it the mainstreaming of Trump=E2=80=99s Ameri=
ca, or an even broader cultural shift?

Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Earlier this week, before heading to New Orleans for the Super Bowl, Fox Co=
rp.
chairman and C.E.O. Lachlan Murdoch kicked off the company=E2=80=99s earnin=
gs call by touting a record $781 million in EBITDA for the quarter, fueled =
by 20 percent growth in advertising revenue=E2=80=94a surge that Murdoch at=
tributed to the presidential election and live sports. The future looked si=
milarly bright: Fox had long ago sold out its inventory for Sunday=E2=80=99=
s Chiefs-Eagles game =E2=80=9Cwith record pricing,=E2=80=9D capping a posts=
eason in which it had enjoyed its highest-ever pricing and demand for NFL
games. None of this was surprising, of course; ever since Rupert sold his e=
ntertainment empire to Disney, Fox has practically become a live-programmin=
g pure play=E2=80=94and the strategy=E2=80=99s success has been evident fro=
m the company=E2=80=99s performance.

=C2=A0

What Lachlan said next was even more remarkable, though: Since the election=
 in November, Fox News had seen =E2=80=9Cincreased demand from existing blu=
e
chip advertisers as well as new clients coming to the network due to its re=
cord share of audience,=E2=80=9D which now comprises 70 percent of cable ne=
ws viewership. Asked to elaborate, Lachlan specified that Fox News had, sin=
ce the election, added =E2=80=9Cover 100 new clients who have not been Fox =
News advertisers=E2=80=9D and that he expected more inbound as the cable ne=
twork=E2=80=99s ratings and revenue increased in the next quarter.

=C2=A0

Fox Corp.=E2=80=99s ad sales chief, Jeff Collins, later told me the number =
of new clients actually exceeded 120. He declined to name any of them, oddl=
y, though The Five=E2=80=99s Friday broadcast included creative from Amazon=
, General Motors, and Unilever. (Collins also said that the vast majority o=
f these new clients had not come in as part of Super Bowl=E2=80=93related d=
eals.)

=C2=A0

Yes, advertisers follow audience in this business, but Fox News=E2=80=99s u=
nique place in the ecosystem has long complicated that relationship. Fox ha=
s bested its cable competitors in the ratings for years, historically doubl=
ing MSNBC=E2=80=99s audience and quadrupling CNN=E2=80=99s increasingly mea=
ger haul. By its own account, it has been the top network in basic cable fo=
r the last eight years and the most watched television news channel for the=
 last 22. Nevertheless, it has long struggled to
attract big advertisers, and for all the obvious reasons: The audience for =
cable news is old, averaging around 70 years of age, and the vast majority =
of blue chip advertisers have long been averse to marketing alongside news =
content, particularly political content=E2=80=94and particularly the sort o=
f highly partisan and occasionally batshit crazy stuff that leads to $787 m=
illion defamation settlements. At least, that is, until now.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The influx of such clients is, therefore, quite notable=E2=80=94not just as=
 a business development, but as the sign of a political and cultural shift.=
 =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a big fucking deal,=E2=80=9D veteran media analyst R=
ich Greenfield told me. Historically, Fox News =E2=80=9Cwas, like, ads for =
gold; I couldn=E2=80=99t name a network with worse advertising partners,=E2=
=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CNow, blue chip advertisers like Unilever have come=
 back onto the platform.=E2=80=9D

The Audience of One
-------------------

The renewed acceptance of Fox News is the latest manifestation of a broader
and once-unfathomable transformation in corporate America. In Trump=E2=80=
=99s first administration, nearly every C.E.O. other than Mike Lindell shee=
pishly did their business with the president in the dark while publicly spe=
aking up for diversity and civility and other liberal principles. Now, they=
 embrace Trump openly, making pilgrimages to Mar-a-Lago and standing proudl=
y in the Rotunda while scaling back their D.E.I. initiatives. This corporat=
e embrace of Trump=E2=80=94by
Bezos, Sundar, Tim, etcetera=E2=80=94appears to have opened the door for al=
l of corporate America to go about its business unapologetically and in the=
 open.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Trump=E2=80=99s ascension as a palatable establishment figure has inevitabl=
y elevated his favorite TV network, too. I don=E2=80=99t think I need to re=
hash the myriad ties between Trump and Fox News here=E2=80=94suffice it to
note that Trump=E2=80=99s daughter-in-law Lara just got a job as a host on =
the network, and that former hosts Pete Hegseth and Sean Duffy now serve as=
 the secretaries of Defense and Transportation, respectively, two of the ne=
arly two dozen former Fox personalities and staffers that Trump has hired o=
n in his administration. And in the same way that Fortune 500 companies adv=
ertise in D.C. trade mediacos to reach the executive branch,
clients now appear happy to be adjacent to executives=E2=80=94whether it=E2=
=80=99s OpenAI=E2=80=99s Sam Altman or Meta=E2=80=99s Joel Kaplan=E2=80=94a=
s they go on Fox News=E2=80=99s air to appeal to its audience of one. On Su=
nday, Fox=E2=80=99s Bret Baier will interview Trump in New Orleans ahead of=
 the Super Bowl, which Trump, himself, will attend=E2=80=94possibly even st=
opping by the Murdochs=E2=80=99 suite during the game.

=C2=A0

But attributing Fox=E2=80=99s mainstream-ification to Trump=E2=80=99s succe=
ss is to put the cart before the horse. On some level, Fox=E2=80=99s domina=
nce in television is a byproduct of the same political and cultural forces =
that brought Trump to power. As Collins, the ad sales chief, told me, the F=
ox audience has long been far more diverse=E2=80=94politically, demographic=
ally, etcetera=E2=80=94than the network=E2=80=99s critics want to admit. At=
 this point, he said, the network reaches more Democrats and independents t=
han
both CNN and MSNBC. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a narrative that Fox News does=
 a great job reaching Middle America,=E2=80=9D Collins told me, =E2=80=9Cbu=
t the data shows that it=E2=80=99s actually the entire country.=E2=80=9D Ar=
guably, Trump=E2=80=99s decisive win in November just forced everyone to ac=
knowledge that. =E2=80=9CBrands were avoiding Fox because they didn=E2=80=
=99t like it,=E2=80=9D Greenfield told me. =E2=80=9CNow, they have no choic=
e.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Fox News is not invincible, of course.
Despite its remarkable market share advantage over MSNBC and CNN, it is sti=
ll subject to the same inexorable market forces plaguing those businesses. =
The most obvious is the decline of television=E2=80=99s total addressable m=
arket. And yet, the irony here is that Fox is thriving, in part, because it=
=E2=80=99s buying the dip and investing in live TV news while its competito=
rs are spinning their cable assets out into the wilderness (NBCUniversal) o=
r seemingly preparing to do so (Warner Bros. Discovery).=C2=A0

Meanwhile, the dramatic fragmentation of media that has ostensibly made way=
 for new competitors like Rogan, Tucker, The Daily Wire, and Elon=E2=80=99s=
 X, among others, can also make an institution like Fox News more attractiv=
e to ad buyers. =E2=80=9CIn a fragmented marketplace, it is harder to find =
scaled audiences,=E2=80=9D Collins told me. =E2=80=9CLive sports has been v=
ery successful; as we=E2=80=99re seeing, live news can drive massive reach,=
 as well.=E2=80=9D At
least for now.

