28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The Audience of One</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">The renewed acceptance of Fox News is the latest manifestati=
on of a broader
and once-unfathomable transformation in corporate America. In <strong>Trump=
</strong>=E2=80=99s first administration, nearly every C.E.O. other than <s=
trong>Mike Lindell</strong> sheepishly did their business with the presiden=
t in the dark while publicly speaking up for diversity and civility and oth=
er liberal principles. Now, they embrace Trump openly, making pilgrimages t=
o Mar-a-Lago and standing proudly in the Rotunda while scaling back their D=
=2EE.I. initiatives. This corporate embrace of Trump=E2=80=94by
<strong>Bezos</strong>, <strong>Sundar</strong>, <strong>Tim</strong>, etce=
tera=E2=80=94appears to have opened the door for all of corporate America t=
o go about its business unapologetically and in the open.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Trump=E2=80=99s ascension as a palatable establishment figure has =
inevitably elevated his favorite TV network, too. I don=E2=80=99t think I n=
eed to rehash the myriad ties between Trump and Fox News here=E2=80=94suffi=
ce it to
note that Trump=E2=80=99s daughter-in-law <strong>Lara </strong>just got a =
job as a host on the network, and that former hosts <strong>Pete Hegseth </=
strong>and <strong>Sean Duffy</strong> now serve as the secretaries of Defe=
nse and Transportation, respectively, two of the nearly <em>two dozen </em>=
former Fox personalities and staffers that Trump has hired on in his admini=
stration. And in the same way that <em>Fortune </em>500 companies advertise=
 in D.C. trade mediacos to reach the executive branch,
clients now appear happy to be adjacent to executives=E2=80=94whether it=E2=
=80=99s OpenAI=E2=80=99s <strong>Sam Altman </strong>or Meta=E2=80=99s <str=
ong>Joel Kaplan</strong>=E2=80=94as they go on Fox News=E2=80=99s air to ap=
peal to its audience of one. On Sunday, Fox=E2=80=99s <strong>Bret Baier </=
strong>will interview Trump in New Orleans ahead of the Super Bowl, which T=
rump, himself, will attend=E2=80=94possibly even stopping by the Murdochs=
=E2=80=99 suite during the game.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">But attributing Fox=E2=80=99s mainstream-ification to T=
rump=E2=80=99s success is to put the cart before the horse. On some level, =
Fox=E2=80=99s dominance in television is a byproduct of the same political =
and cultural forces that brought Trump to power. As Collins, the ad sales c=
hief, told me, the Fox audience has long been far more diverse=E2=80=94poli=
tically, demographically, etcetera=E2=80=94than the network=E2=80=99s criti=
cs want to admit. At this point, he said, the network reaches more Democrat=
s and independents than
both CNN and MSNBC. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a narrative that Fox News does=
 a great job reaching Middle America,=E2=80=9D Collins told me, =E2=80=9Cbu=
t the data shows that it=E2=80=99s actually the entire country.=E2=80=9D Ar=
guably, Trump=E2=80=99s decisive win in November just forced everyone to ac=
knowledge that. =E2=80=9CBrands were avoiding Fox because they didn=E2=80=
=99t like it,=E2=80=9D Greenfield told me. =E2=80=9CNow, they have no choic=
e.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Fox News is not invincible, of course.
Despite its remarkable market share advantage over MSNBC and CNN, it is sti=
ll subject to the same inexorable market forces plaguing those businesses. =
The most obvious is the decline of television=E2=80=99s total addressable m=
arket. And yet, the irony here is that Fox is thriving, in part, because it=
=E2=80=99s buying the dip and investing in live TV news while its competito=
rs are spinning their cable assets out into the wilderness (NBCUniversal) o=
r seemingly preparing to do so (Warner Bros. Discovery).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Meanwhile, the dramatic fragmentation of media =
that has ostensibly made way for new competitors like <strong>Rogan</strong=
>, <strong>Tucker</strong>, The Daily Wire, and <strong>Elon</strong>=E2=80=
=99s X, among others, can also make an institution like Fox News more attra=
ctive to ad buyers. =E2=80=9CIn a fragmented marketplace, it is harder to f=
ind scaled audiences,=E2=80=9D Collins told me. =E2=80=9CLive sports has be=
en very successful; as we=E2=80=99re seeing, live news can drive massive re=
ach, as well.=E2=80=9D At
least for now.</p></div>
